unittitle.value: International Longshoremen's Association: Reference Files Compiled by the International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union

abstract.value: In 1986, the International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union (ILWU) de-accessioned reference files from its Anne Rand Research Library pertaining to its rival, the New York-based International Longshoremen's Association (ILA), and donated them to the Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives at New York University. The militant ILWU, representing West Coast longshoremen, had once been part of the ILA, but broke away during the bitter labor and political struggles of the mid-1930s. This contentious history forms the backdrop to the ILWU's amassing of extensive reference files on the ILA and its travails. The reference files include handbills, contracts, proceedings, internal documents, and newspaper clippings from the <title render="italic">New York Times</title>, the <title render="italic">Wall Street Journal</title>, the <title render="italic">Journal of Commerce</title>and other trade and labor papers â€“ many of them documenting charges of fraud and racketeering on the New York City waterfront.

p.value: Published citations should take the following form: <lb/><lb/>Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library <lb/>70 Washington Square South <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.
Donated by the International Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union, 1986. The accession number associated with this gift is 1986.006.

This contentious history forms the backdrop to the ILWU's amassing of extensive reference files on the ILA and its travails. This collection represents an unusual glimpse of a union's serious effort to monitor the fortunes of a rival labor organization -- in this case, a rival with which it had once been affiliated.
Several runs of serials, including the ILA's rank-and-file publication <title render="italic">Shape-Up</title>, have been removed from the collection and catalogued as part of the Tamiment Library.
